Static :-
   Why we use static 

Original code for reusion :-

class RecursionExample {
    static int factorial(int n) {
        if (n == 1) {  // ğŸ›‘ Base case: Stop when n = 1
            return 1;
        }
        return n * factorial(n - 1); // ğŸ” Recursive call: Call itself
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int num = 5;
        System.out.println("Factorial of " + num + " is: " + factorial(num));
    }
}

Question :- Why we use static there 
 Why Use static?
ğŸ‘‰ In Java, if we call a method inside main(), it must be either:
âœ… A static method
âœ… Called using an object

Since main() is static, it can only call another static method directly.

If we remove static, the compiler will give an error saying:

"Cannot make a static reference to a non-static method"
(Meaning: main() is static, but factorial() isnâ€™t, so it wonâ€™t work.)


  ğŸ“Œ What If We Don't Use static?
If we remove static, we need to create an object to call the function:

class RecursionExample {
    int factorial(int n) {
        if (n == 1) return 1;
        return n * factorial(n - 1);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        RecursionExample obj = new RecursionExample(); // ğŸ‘ˆ Create an object
        System.out.println("Factorial of 5: " + obj.factorial(5)); 
    }
}

ğŸ“Œ 1ï¸âƒ£ What Does static Mean?
ğŸ‘‰ In Java, static means "belongs to the class, not to objects."
ğŸ‘‰ If a method or variable is static, it is shared among all objects of the class.

ğŸ”´ Without static â†’ Each object has its own copy of the method/variable.
ğŸŸ¢ With static â†’ There is only one copy, shared by all objects.

   
class Student {
    static String college = "MVIT"; // ğŸ‘ˆ `static` variable (shared)
    String name; // ğŸ‘ˆ Normal variable (unique for each object)

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println(name + " studies at " + college);
    }
}

public class StaticExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Gayathri");
        Student s2 = new Student("Jaya");

        s1.show();
        s2.show();
    }
}
ğŸ“Œ 1ï¸âƒ£ Can We Change a static Variable?
Yes, we can change a static variable! But when we change it, it affects all objects because static variables are shared.

ğŸ”´ Example:

class Student {
    static String college = "MVIT"; // ğŸ‘ˆ Static variable (shared)
    String name;

    Student(String name) {
        this.name = name;
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println(name + " studies at " + college);
    }
}
public class StaticChangeExample {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s1 = new Student("Gayathri");
        Student s2 = new Student("Jaya");

        s1.show(); // âœ… MVIT
        s2.show(); // âœ… MVIT

        // ğŸ”¥ Change the static variable
        s1.college = "IIT Madras"; 

        s1.show(); // âŒ Now changed to "IIT Madras"
        s2.show(); // âŒ Now changed to "IIT Madras"
    }
}

ğŸ“Œ 2ï¸âƒ£ But, What's the Right Way?
ğŸ‘‰ Instead of s1.college, it's better to use Student.college because college is static.

ğŸ”´ Better Way:

Student.college = "IIT Madras"; // âœ… Best way
ğŸ‘‰ Why?
Because college belongs to the class, not just s1. Using Student.college makes it clear that we are changing a static variable.
